<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="1" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD BGCOLOR="#add8ff" WIDTH="150"><B>Analysis</B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD ALIGN="left" WIDTH="150">Having concluded that the merger here in<BR ALIGN='left'/>question constituted an &quot;F&quot;<BR ALIGN='left'/>reorganization under § 368(a) (1), we<BR ALIGN='left'/>turn to the problem of determining the<BR ALIGN='left'/>loss which Stauffer New Mexico is<BR ALIGN='left'/>entitled to carry back and of<BR ALIGN='left'/>determining to which of the three pre-<BR ALIGN='left'/>merger corporations the loss may be<BR ALIGN='left'/>carried. As discussed, supra, had the<BR ALIGN='left'/>merger been effected in a number of<BR ALIGN='left'/>other ways, the loss sustained by<BR ALIGN='left'/>Stauffer New Mexico, to the extent that<BR ALIGN='left'/>it represented the loss of Stauffer<BR ALIGN='left'/>California, could have been carried back<BR ALIGN='left'/>to a pre-merger taxable year of Stauffer<BR ALIGN='left'/>California. But for the simultaneous<BR ALIGN='left'/>merger of the three corporations, the<BR ALIGN='left'/>loss carryback would have been<BR ALIGN='left'/>undeniably allowed. This, the<BR ALIGN='left'/>Commissioner admits.</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
>]
	"3cuUmx2QEV" [label=<
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="1" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="4">
